Spotlight

US-Canada bridge tensions

What happened? President Trump threatened to block the Gordie Howe International Bridge, a 1.5-mile bridge connecting Detroit and Windsor, Ontario. He demanded that Canada turn over at least half of the bridge's ownership and agree to other unspecified demands as the rift between Washington and Ottawa deepens. The publicly owned bridge, shared by Canada and Michigan, is nearly complete and designated as an official US port of entry.

Criticism: Trump accused Canada of treating the US unfairly and argued Washington should share in the economic benefits of the bridge. He also claimed Canada controls the project and that no American steel was used, calling it disadvantageous to US interests. Canadian PM Mark Carney rejected those assertions, pointing to the 2012 Canada-Michigan Crossing Agreement, which establishes joint public ownership and confirms the use of both US and Canadian labor and steel.

History: The bridge, which spans the Detroit River and is named after late Canadian hockey legend Gordie Howe, who played for the Detroit Red Wings. Construction began in 2018, and its estimated expense is $4.73B. The organization developing the bridge, the Windsor-Detroit Bridge Authority, is a Canadian federal Crown corporation, wholly owned by the government.

Fact: On Jan 30, the US Department of Homeland Security declared that the bridge would serve as an official port of entry and would save travelers $12.7M annually.

Google shares personal data

What happened? Google complied with a subpoena from Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) seeking extensive personal data on student activist and journalist Amandla Thomas-Johnson. The request stemmed from his brief attendance at a pro-Palestinian protest in 2024 while studying at Cornell University in NY. Google shared IP addresses, mobile numbers, subscriber information, and bank account details associated with his account.

Criticism: The US government is reportedly using a controversial legal tool, an administrative subpoena, to compel tech companies to hand over private user data. These requests have targeted individuals critical of the Trump administration, including anonymous Instagram accounts that share information about ICE raids, as well as people who publicly protest or criticize Trump and his policies. It is believed that ICE may be seeking this information to identify, monitor, and potentially detain those individuals.

Argument: Administrative subpoenas allow federal agencies request user information without court approval. While they cannot access email content or search histories, they can demand metadata and identifying details to unmask account holders. Companies are not legally required to comply, but Google says its privacy policy permits data sharing in response to enforceable government requests.
 

Long story short

Global Affairs

Indonesia is preparing to send up to 8,000 troops to Gaza to be part of a peacekeeping force under Trump’s second phase of his peace plan. This marks the first outside force on the territory since 1967. The plan has a mandate from the UN Security Council to establish an International Stabilization Force, which will help secure border areas in Gaza and ensure the territory's demilitarisation, including the disarmament of Hamas (phase II).

Zimbabwe’s cabinet approved draft legislation to extend President Emmerson Mnangagwa's term until 2030. Under the proposal, presidents would be chosen by MPs rather than in a direct vote and could serve a maximum of two seven-year terms. Public consultations would be held before the bill heads to parliament for debate, where both chambers are dominated by the ruling Zanu-PF party (constitutional changes).

Business & Markets

Vega Security raised $120M in a Series B round to redefine the traditional security detection and response model. The two-year-old startup, valued at $700M, aims to replace legacy SIEM systems like Splunk by running AI-native threat detection directly in cloud services and data lakes. Vega says its decentralized approach reduces expenses and complexity (security revamp).

Paramount Skydance enhanced its $108.4B bid for Warner Bros Discovery by offering a 25-cent-per-share quarterly ticking fee from 2027 if the agreement is delayed. It also agreed to cover WBD’s $2.8B breakup fee owed to Netflix. The move counters Netflix's pursuit of Warner Bros. studios, franchises like DC and "Game of Thrones," and networks including CNN. Paramount also boosted regulatory progress and financing guarantees (sweetened proposal).

The US Federal Aviation Administration expects Canada to announce Gulfstream certifications for some business jets that have been delayed for years. The move follows a dispute that escalated after President Trump threatened to decertify Bombardier planes and impose tariffs. Aviation experts cautioned against politicizing aircraft certification, warning of broader risks to global aviation norms (jet dispute eases).

Science & Tech

Facebook rolled out a fresh AI-powered feature aimed at boosting creative expression. The updates include animated profile pictures and a “Restyle” tool that lets users transform Stories and Memories into anime, ethereal, glowy styles, or custom moods, lighting, and backdrops via text prompts. Additionally, text posts support animated backgrounds such as falling leaves or ocean waves (fresh update).

Researchers at the University of Geneva found that tumors can reprogram neutrophils (typically infection-fighting immune cells) into cancer-promoting agents. Once inside the tumor microenvironment, neutrophils begin producing the chemokine CCL3, which fuels tumor growth. By selectively disabling CCL3, scientists showed neutrophils stopped supporting cancer, identifying the molecule as a potential marker of tumor progression across multiple cancer types (cancer’s immune switch).
